For {= vendor_product =}+ public real-estate development software vendor-products, supply {= workflow_axis =}+ source-backed workflow observations per product, with at least {= url =}+ URL for each observation. The work is descriptive public provenance: record what sources say a product does, how pricing is publicly stated when it is stated, and what market or localization evidence is actually source-stated. Do not rank vendors, recommend tools, advise on procurement or zoning law, infer Israeli regulatory compliance, score leads, discover contacts, or plan outreach.

Use these workflow labels:
{=% for axis, aliases in workflow_axes.items() =%}
- `{= axis =}`: {= aliases[:4] | join(", ") =}
{=% endfor =%}

Products can be full feasibility platforms or narrower tools for zoning/planning analysis, massing/site optimization, pro forma or underwriting, development deal workflow, data/API integrations, or local planning-data workflows. Public pricing absence, quote-only pricing, source-date absence, rebrands, acquisitions, product-family ambiguity, and source-class conflicts are useful observations when they are attached to a product that otherwise has source-backed workflow evidence. Null-only products and unsupported blanks do not count as provenance.

Good source roles include official product pages, pricing pages, documentation, case studies, official marketplaces, partner or integration pages, public procurement listings, reputable proptech / AEC / CRE coverage, and analyst or vendor profiles. Generic software directories, listicles, startup profiles, and broad "AI real estate" pages can help discovery, but they should not by themselves carry official product existence, vendor pricing, or core feature evidence.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the submitted vendor-product, or a clearly equivalent product family / renamed product from the same vendor.
- The page must connect the product to real-estate development feasibility, site planning, zoning/planning analysis, massing/site optimization, financial/pro forma modeling, development deal workflow, pricing-model evidence, or integrations/localization for such workflows.
- The page's source role must fit the workflow observation. Vendor pricing needs a vendor-controlled or official marketplace source; source-stated localization or market presence needs a source-stated geography signal; core capability observations need product-specific feature, documentation, case-study, marketplace, partner, or reputable trade evidence rather than a shallow directory blurb.
- The page must support a concrete, source-bounded observation for the workflow label: a feature, pricing model, integration, coverage claim, market/localization claim, customer/case-study use, visible source date, or named missing/conflict state that the source makes checkable.
